21:50.263 --> 21:53.427
activation analysis.

21:56.490 --> 22:00.975
Neutron activation analysis is a very important 
part of of nuclear reactor research, the users of

22:02.407 --> 22:06.674
these facilities. Even the small reactors, you 
can provide this service. The little 201, for

22:11.862 --> 22:25.744
example, on campus, you could do a small amount of 
what we call the NAA on it, simply because neutrons

22:11.862 --> 22:25.744
are present. Neutrons, when they enter a 
substance, They interreact with the nuclei and in

22:30.250 --> 22:37.100
that process the radioactivity is produced. Each 
element that's present becomes radioactive. And

22:41.907 --> 22:50.018
then it's up to the scientist to have the technique 
and the skills to identify what he's made

22:41.907 --> 22:50.018
radioactive. In doing so he can quantify what's in 
the sample. That's really all we do. As well as If he

23:00.845 --> 23:17.261
runs standards of known weights, known masses, he 
can then compare the unknown sample to a known

23:00.845 --> 23:17.261
sample and then determine the quantity of the 
material that's present. So it's a full analysis

23:17.281 --> 23:21.385
of the sample. You can do this by chemistry as well, 
but there are some big advantages in many cases by

23:26.917 --> 23:34.567
doing it with neutron, the neutron method rather 
than the chemical method. Very good explanation.

