23:39.954 --> 23:41.636
what it is. That's what it is. And then the other 
work we got into in the early days was to work with

23:42.778 --> 23:55.995
our beam ports, which are penetrations through 
the reactor shield structure They're much like

23:56.819 --> 24:00.323
large telescopes, the way they're fabricated 
there. They start near the reactor with a small

24:00.843 --> 24:19.622
diameter pipe, and then as you work your way 
through the shield structure, these sections of

24:00.843 --> 24:19.622
pipes get larger, which allows you to place 
shielding material in the pipes and leave, say, a

24:00.843 --> 24:19.622
tiny hole through the center. If you line the hole 
up all the way through the port, you will get a beam

24:24.325 --> 24:52.915
of radiation coming down the hole and you can shape 
that beam have it large or you can have it very small

24:24.325 --> 24:52.915
you can place materials in the beam and if you don't 
want to look at what would be coming directly off

24:24.325 --> 24:52.915
the reactor you can do what we call secondary 
reactions

24:24.325 --> 24:52.915
allow the neutrons to interact with the target and 
then you indeed then look at that target through

24:53.738 --> 24:57.883
the beam. Let whatever the secondary reactions 
are come down the beam. And in the 60s and the years

25:02.349 --> 25:16.828
prior to that, 40s, 50s, there was a lot of particle 
physics

25:02.349 --> 25:16.828
going on. These studies were being conducted at 
research reactors.

25:23.843 --> 25:27.346
Of course, the cyclotron or accelerators came 
into being. That gave the scientists another tool

25:28.167 --> 25:31.550
to work with. Again, you're involved with 
radioactivity when you work with a cyclotron or an

25:32.851 --> 25:38.577
accelerator. It's a different machine entirely 
than a nuclear reactor. The scientist uses it for a

25:43.902 --> 25:46.464
different reason. But our beam port work became 
quite extensive. mid-60s all the way up through

25:54.590 --> 25:56.732
early 70s. And then it seemed like so much of this 
work was being done all over the world and in the

25:59.135 --> 26:16.955
national laboratories, mainly here in the United 
States, that it seemed like they reached a point

25:59.135 --> 26:16.955
where they figured they'd studied most of the 
major things. And the interest in particle

26:17.695 --> 26:24.563
physics using a reactor kind of died away. And it 
wasn't until a few years later that other uses were

26:26.298 --> 26:34.729
found for extracting beams. Neutron 
radiography, for example, is a very popular

26:36.732 --> 26:55.377
common method now for use of a neutron beam to image 
an object by measuring the transmission of

26:36.732 --> 26:55.377
neutrons through that object. and obtaining the 
image on the film, much like an x-ray would be done,

26:56.386 --> 27:15.148
except the nuclear particle you're dealing with 
is much different, and it interreacts with matter

26:56.386 --> 27:15.148
in a much different way than the x-ray would.

27:15.168 --> 27:24.739
